article.description: Baron Davis made a pull-up 3-pointer with less than a second left in overtime and the Golden State Warriors broke their first losing streak of the season with a 110-107 win.
article.headline: Davis' last-second 3-pointer in OT sinks Sonics
article.linkText: Davis' 3-pointer in OT halts Warriors' losing streak
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Derek Fisher carried the Golden State Warriors with guile and experience, before Baron Davis applied the finishing touch. These are not the same old Warriors. Davis made a pull-up 3-pointer with less than a second left in overtime and Golden State Warriors broke its first losing streak of the season with a 110-107 win over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. Davis took the inbound pass from Mike Dunleavy near midcourt, then stopped and drained the 26-footer over Seattle's Ronald Murray. Davis had previously missed a difficult shot in the lane at the end of regulation sending the game to overtime. "Resiliency, man, resiliency," Davis said. "That's what it's all about, those moments to make big shots, big plays." While Davis came through at the end, it was the play of Fisher -- the elder-statesman on Golden State's youthful roster -- that kept the Warriors close. Fisher scored a season-high 26 points and carried the Warriors in the fourth quarter with 10 points. In overtime, he scored five points, including a 3-pointer to start the extra period. Fisher was just three points off his career high of 29 against the Los Angeles Lakers last year. "The first shot that went through the basket I knew, as long as I continued to get looks at the basket, I would have a good night," said Fisher, who made 8 of 16 shots and was 8-for-8 at the free throw line. "Every night is going to be an adventure for us, because we're a young team. We like to just get out and play basketball." The win snapped a brief two-game skid for the Warriors, who lost close home games to Phoenix and Detroit last week, and provided a positive start for a five-game East Coast swing that begins after a game Wednesday night at home against Houston. Ray Allen scored a season-high 35 points for Seattle, and put to rest talk of a shooting slump with his second straight strong performance. He made 11 of 24 shots and seven 3-pointers, but missed a running 3-pointer as time expired. Tied at 98 after regulation, Allen scored Seattle's first five points of overtime, then made perfect passes to Nick Collison for a dunk and layup to give Seattle a 107-105 lead with 1:05 left. Dunleavy made a pull-up jumper to draw even, but Allen and Davis exchanged misses, and Seattle called timeout with 22.9 left. Allen drove the lane, but his left-handed finger-roll over Adonal Foyle came up short and Foyle grabbed the rebound. Golden State called timeout, setting up Davis' final shot. "Adonal made some big defensive plays at the end that kept them from getting buckets," Warriors' coach Mike Montgomery said. "Hopefully, we'll get some confidence in our ability to close games in the end." Davis finished with 21 points and 13 assists, but was mostly quiet in the fourth quarter, going scoreless until a lob-dunk on an inbound pass from Fisher with 54 seconds left, giving the Warriors a 96-93 lead. Allen answered with a 3-pointer to tie, and Fisher made two free throws with 25 seconds left. Murray drove the lane, getting fouled by Davis with 4.2 left, and made both free throws to pull even at 98. Dunleavy and Richardson both finished with 16 for the Warriors. Richardson carried Golden State early, with 10 points in the first quarter. Troy Murphy added 14 points and 14 rebounds and Calbert Chaney scored 10 off the bench. Typically mild-mannered and docile coach Bob Weiss picked up two technical fouls within 12 seconds early in the fourth quarter and was ejected, igniting the sluggish Sonics. Weiss screamed at official Bennie Adams after Danny Fortson was called for a flagrant foul on Davis with 11:10 left, and then went onto the court, yelling at Adams when he called a block on Fortson 12 seconds later. "Danny drew the charge and the call went against him. That's when it happened," Weiss said. "I thought Danny was there. Things have been going against him." Murray added 17 off the bench for Seattle, Collison had 14 and Reggie Evans 13. Rashard Lewis struggled, making just 4 of 17 shots and finished with 12. Seattle shot just 37 percent.

Game notes
Assistant Bob Hill took over after Weiss was ejected. ... Fortson returned from a one-game suspension for his actions while being ejected last Friday at Utah and was promptly hit with a technical foul in the second quarter. ... It was the first overtime game for Golden State. Seattle previously beat Minnesota and Toronto in OT.
